It is clearly a crime that the Greatest Model Of All Time seems not to be available in a teeny form so hopefully this goes some way to fixing that.

This is a reworking of Miffles (now sadly) 'missing' (üôÑ) dreadnought; I've included those files in the 'miffles original' folder. I started this years ago and only dug it out again recently. Alas, my CAD skills are very much in the noob-zone (hence the name of the model) so apologies for both the woeful nature of some of the hack-n-slashing and also the resulting files sizes. I'm revving up a campaign of nagging any of those Legends of our hobby (Woddish, Jimmyzimms, KMFP, Daffmakes, Mildseven etc) to actually do it properly. Fingers crossed :).

This is the Grim version, over which I have plastered a load of bolts and various other gubbins. I've included a load of body versions, with different torso angles and feet orientations: I'm sure you'll work it all out from the file names. I've also included looser-fitting mount options in case your resin tolerance can't take the snugger version. The identifier 'small' for the legs is in juxtaposition to a 'large' version I trialled (about 110% enbiggening of legs). I like the Deadpool-2-re-growing look of the originals but if any of you want something that looks a bit less top-heavy then let me know and I might finish the re-work.

I've done 'TrueScale' (top of head, not to eye) 8mm versions and also 10mm for easier re-scaling (so, for example, if you game in 18mm just print at 180%).

I may also do another upload with some non-bolty Tech monopose versions, with the larger legs, for a more hard-scif vibe.

Cheers

Kipples

PS: The '0-mount' identifier in the file names means I haven't put any mount rings on the body. I've tried this for the Tech version, though, which has a single ring spacer for the mounts so they're less flush with the torso.

Genetically engineered Marines travel throughout Space, battling depraved heretics, dishonourable traitors, and vile aliens.

This set includes 4 powered gauntlets, two holding the torn off heads of two different types of alien beast - a brutal ork, and a sinister soulstealer. The third holds a retro style space beaky helmet, and the fourth is empty, perhaps for you to add in your own head model! All four have supported versions.

This is an updated version of the first thing I ever tried to 'sculpt', as opposed to arrange geometric shapes - an ork head. It's a little reflection on my part, comparing where I started to where I am. It's been a slow process, as I take what digital hobby time I can in between physical modelling and all my other fickle interests! But it's still nice to see what I feel in some improvement.

You can see the original here:
https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/power-gauntlet-prime-scale-powered-gauntlet-holding-head

I am an amateur enthusiast 3D designer, and appreciate all constructive feedback. Please check out my other designs for more wargame models, and please consider following me, posting a make, or even leaving a donation via my profile!

My own take on a Super Heavy aerial transport for Space Marines dubbed the Storm Crane. Sized to be used in Epic/Legion Imperialis games.

Unique in its role, Storm Cranes are able to deliver a variety of assets to the front. From 10 fully embarked rhinos, or 4 kratos heavy battle tanks or any other armored detachment, Storm Cranes are able to bring full detachments of armor needed on the battle field. Protected by heavy plating and a pair of void shields this flyer can withstand any punishment short of anti-titan weapons. Ensuring its cargo successfully arrives where it is needed. Each Strom Crane is armed with two audax heavy bolter arrays and two titan sized havoc launchers making it a formidable assault craft that can break through enemy lines. A truly armored work horse, Space Marine legions relied heavily on these vehicles throughout the crusade and into the Heresy.


While I designed most of this using 3D Builder, I did borrow some choice parts from free kits.
Winglets/Audax Turrets from MKHand Industries
Thruster Turbine and Exhaust from IronMaster
Titan Hatch and Void Shields from Danny_Cyanide

A humble reworking of Moonjammy's excellent designs, optimised for stackable printing.

Love printing little dudes but hate having to get up every hour to scrape off your build plate, waste good resin in your wash station, and restart the print? Then here's the new easy-to-use stacking solution you've been waiting for! Stack small objects vertically to fit into your print schedule, or efficiently fill left over build plate volume when printing taller objects.

Including:
- **Galactic Crusader Infantry in Heavy Siege Armour** with a choice of Boxing Gloves or Hedge Trimmers and a selection of heavy weaponry
- Arranged in pre-built stacks of 12, 18 and 24.
- Raw components and a guide for creating custom stacks

**Scale and Sizing:**
The Galactic Crusaders in this pack have been resized to 105%.
This makes the average Galactic Crusader ~9.5mm tall (varying based on pose and armour style), and the base plugs 6.16x1.31mm.

A humble presentation of an excellent contribution from
[DaffMakes](https://cults3d.com/en/users/DaffMakes/3d-models), reworking excellent original designs by Moonjammy, DangitBobby, and Woddish.

Need some more hatch options to keep your Legions of tanks looking fresh? How's about 45 new options!

Including:
- Tank Commanders in 6 poses
- Pintle Gunners with 3 weapon options
- All options come in 5 Galactic Crusader armour styles
- All options come in Windowed hatches (suitable for most vehicles) or Riveted hatches (suitable for Sig-RN vehicles)

TODO:
- Support Riveted options
- Add Lychee file (_The file I was working on decided to self-destruct

*Like what... DaffMakes is doing!? Check out his [Cults page](https://cults3d.com/en/users/DaffMakes/3d-models), where he's breathing new life into the Galactic Crusaders, or his [Ko-Fi](https://ko-fi.com/daffmakes)*

Description :

1
2
3
4
5
6

This is a remix of the impressive STROGANOFF original Epic Scale Landing Craft found at https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/epic-scale-landing-craft. As I wanted to print it on FDM I modified it to have the less non-fdm printable detail removed (turrets, landing gear) and those details later printed in a resin printer for accuracy.
There is some work in the lateral clamps as I have added a 4mm magnet slot and modified the width to fit new rhinos/big grimdark containers.

* 2024-02-10 Update: Add missing lower rear reactor piece and update renders

I have explicitly asked STROGANOFF for modifying and sharing this asset. Be respectful with your fellow artists :)

A humble reworking of Speacock and THEWRAETHTHU's excellent reworking of Failtruck's (?) excellent design, optimised and cleaned up for easy printing.

"_While P.O.D. Droplets were usually synonymous with lightning assaults, one of their most infamous uses during the Hera-C involved an over-eager commander ordering the launch of a wave long before his logistics ships had made it into orbit._

_When the P.O.D.s finally made planetfall some six months later, the confused defenders found nothing inside but dust and emaciated corpses..._"

- Reassembled and repaired: No more voids!
- Hollowed for efficient printing: Including rafts and supports, small P.O.D.s use ~3.8ml of resin, large P.O.D.s use ~5.4ml of resin
- Includes supported and unsupported STLs and Lychee scenes for tweaking

How hungry are they?
So hungry they could eat an entire planet.

Variety of chainaxe wielding maniacs in segmented armour pattern.
Comes with regular helm, Sarum helm, and Hungry Boys Veteran helm for all pose types.

Extra variety can be gotten by mirroring the various poses. In particular with the dual and two-handed chainaxe variants.

For the flying marines, they have holes in the jump pack to accept a 1mm rod as a flight stand. For my example (see my generic assault marines), I cut halfway along the curve of a paperclip, inserted the curved end into the hole with a bit of superglue and adjusted the tilt of the marine from there. Then, drill a hole into your base of choice, and adjust the height of the paperclip as desired.

There is also a "_standoffs" version. This is something I'm playing around with where the models' feet are offset from the plug, allowing you to use the plug as a stand when painting, and then slice or snip off the small cylinders to allow you to glue the feet directly onto the base, for a seamless finish.

If you'd rather adjust the placement of the rods yourself for use with straight brass rod, or clear acrylic rods, I've provided the "_nohole" versions for this purpose.

Thanks to Moonjammy for the excellent original models!

OK, just a scooped, supported and magnet ready version of Wolfkeeper's GRIMDARK MINUTE FLYING ARMED TRANSPORT and nitramthx's burning little dino for galactic crusaders. They are great little free files and will work well at 8mm. I sized them to have roughly a 70mm wingspan, but size however you like, just be cognicent that resizing circles can make ovals.

I removed the lower floor of the model, so the magent insert is on the roof of the model and can accept magnets up to 10mm - so pick your poison.

I also did some editing to make sure there were no resin captures.

These models are not hollowed in the traditional sense - no resin can be captured and all internals can be exposed to UV light for curing. Some idiot will not look at the files and mis-understand that and will invariably do an "aktuallly blah blah blah" - it always seems to happen....

All your sponson needs, all in one place!

A central collection so I don't have to update a half dozen packs when modifying the sponsons, and the Universal Sponson Pin needed for the Magnetic Sponson System.

**Wait a minute, Magnetic Sponson System?**

The Magnetic Sponson System is an easy way to swap out sponson weapons. Want to change up loadouts between battles, or need to replace a snapped barrel? Just slide the old sponsons out and new ones in!

Each pin has slots for a normal sponson weapon and a 2x1mm neodymium magnet.

The pins are symmetrical, so there is no need to mirror them. Just remember the rivets point backwards, and make sure to decide on which polarity to use for the left and right pins!

**Note:** This is currently compatible with the Pred-8R, SIG-RN, and Crete-S packs.

A slightly unhinged reworking of Moonjammy's excellent design, optimised for _crazy_ printing!

A new concept for creating simple, stackable supports for Epic scale infantry! Use the supplied STLs or easily create blocks of infantry in any arbitrary width and height simply by copying strips in Lychee and moving them vertically, no additional fine-tuning required!

**ARE STACKABLE SUPPORTS RIGHT FOR ME?**

Stackable supports are slightly less resin-efficient compared with printing a single squad flat on the build plate, but time and clean-up efficient, allowing you to print large numbers of troops in a single print without having to get up to scrape them off the build plate, clean up, and restart your print every hour!

Stackable supports also allow you to make effective use of empty space on your build plate when printing larger vehicles or 28mm scale models. Just create a stack as tall as your other models!

**UH OH, THIS LOOKS COMPLICATED! IS REMOVING THE SUPPORTS HARD?**

De-supporting these is easy and risk free!
The heavy supports only make contact with the pseudo-rafts so you can yank them off without any worries. Then just use a knife tip or tweezer to pick off the remaining supports on the individual models.

A slightly unhinged reworking of Moonjammy's excellent design, optimised for _crazy_ printing!

A new concept for creating simple, stackable supports for Epic scale infantry! Create blocks of infantry in any arbitrary width and height simply by copying strips in Lychee and moving them vertically, no additional fine-tuning required!

**ARE STACKABLE SUPPORTS RIGHT FOR ME?**

Stackable supports are resin-inefficient compared with printing a single squad flat on the build plate, but time and clean-up efficient, allowing you to print large numbers of troops in a single print without having to get up to scrape them off the build plate, clean up, and restart your print every hour!

Stackable supports also allow you to make effective use of empty space on your build plate when printing larger vehicles or 28mm scale models. Just create a stack as tall as your other models!

**UH OH, THIS LOOKS COMPLICATED! IS REMOVING THE SUPPORTS HARD?**

De-supporting these is easy and risk free!
The heavy supports only make contact with the pseudo-rafts so you can yank them off without any worries. Then just use a knife tip or tweezer to pick off the remaining supports on the individual models.

**I THINK MARK 2s ARE STUPID! ARE YOU GOING TO SUPPORT OTHER TYPES OF INFANTRY?**

Probably! Eventually! But until I get round to it, feel free to try this style of supporting on your own models üòÅ

***THIS IS A WORK IN PROGRESS***

Tiny troops which are perfect for giving your games of epic conflict a sense of epic scale. And what can be more perfect than the golden perfect winged assault cherubs?

Building on the foundation that Moonjam left us, I've remodeled and rebuilt most of the base Galactic Crusader parts into higher detailed versions that will allow those of you with 8k and 12k printers to showcase your models with. In addition, the figures are easily to print at 200% (maybe even 400%?) for use with other games systems and scales.

The blender source is included containing my hobo-rigged figures and pose library. I wasn't feeling all too well and took some liberties/shortcuts than I would for a more generic release but should get you most of the way even when I used basic object parenting for a few parts. Sorry =/

Figures have been run through 3DBuilder to merge and decimate the meshes to reasonable levels though you can export your own from the Blend. I've also uploaded a zip of just the unmerged undecimated figures for your further use if so desired. Not that plinths, risers, and banner icons are NOT merged so you can rework or replace stuff as works for you.

Big shouts out to Moonjam for the base content to build on. Icons from Lord Chronos. Heads based on work from M3rcurymordbid.

If you like what I did and want to leave a tip it would be appreciated.
https://paypal.me/jimmyzimms

Thank you to MoonJam and Lord_Arner for many of the base parts!

Some Power Armoured Grey Knights for your Epic needs. These are scaled as 8mm marines like all of Moonjam's stuff. There are all the options needed for the current NetEA Developmental GK list. Everything for Strike Squads, Purgation Squads, Purifier Squads, Interceptor Squads, and even a little Crowe for good measure.

I have included supported .lys files for those who don't want the hassle of supporting them yourself. The supports are way more janky and not as nice as MoonJam's, but they do print. I have test printed them and they work.

Just a note, the painted models in the preview are from a previous version before purity seals were added. May the Emperor have mercy on your eyes when you are painting these.

These are largely based off of MoonJam's amazing Galactic Crusaders. I also took the helmets from Lord_Arner's Daybreak Strikers. There is also a Plaguebearer head for which I cannot find the link from jimjimjimmyjim in there so thanks to him as well. A few bits were my own design but the credit should really be theirs. Do you find an endless rain of bullets overwhelming your plastic men? Do they need to carry a list of all their favorite vacation spots with them on the battlefield? Do you hate having generic accessories on those tiny plastic arms? If so, this may be the kit for you.

The skull is the legendary Brexit skull.

If you print it, please post a make! If you really like it, consider sending a tip!

These were made from scratch using base primitives.

A game buddy asked for some prints and I couldn't find a suitable model.

As per 2nd pic...

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2626812
- The shape is heavily borrowed from a similar model on $h@p#w@y$.

While i very much like Mkhand's models (and have printed a number for my Imperial fleet) i've found that the wings are very delicate on my filament printer... as such the thunderhawk wings are all a little chunkier (minimum 0.5mm).

Has now been netfabb'd.

Have test printed. works but it's like tiny tiny (as per last pic).
Re pic: the small ones are what the file produces. the big one is 250% scale just to test that stuff was there and printing.
Re other pic: (not finished) paint just to add some colour.
The teeny-tiny ones do look ok once they're on stands. And there's a fair amount of tricky support cleanup. enjoy.

Note: For my marine fleet i've printed these at 133%. just to get a bit more 'detail' and less blobbular. these are the yellowish ones. note that for sticking them to the bases i just use some chopped filament, was easier than printing the bases with stands as they were coming out horrible.

A re-design of the original miniature produced by Games Workshop for their 6mm scale table top wargame, Epic 40,000 (and precessors/successors). They have since abandoned all support for Epic, so I modeled this in Autodesk Inventor for any avid wargamers who don't want to use proxies or pay through the nose for OOP official models off Ebay.

I haven't tried printing this model in an FDM printer so I can't recommend settings or methods of optimization.

Epic has been re-released as a titans-only game called Adeptus Titanicus. It is nominally 8mm scale instead of 6mm, so I suggest that anyone wanting to print this for AT scenery or to play 8mm Epic should upscale it by 125%.
